# GitHub Repo Health Monitor — Cursor Rules
# ============================================================
# This file tells Cursor exactly how this project is structured
# so it generates correct code without asking questions.

## Project Purpose
Multi-agent system that analyses any public GitHub repository
and produces a health score, verdict, and actionable report.

## Architecture — Read This First
LangGraph StateGraph with 4 nodes:

  fetch_repo
      ↓
  run_parallel  (Activity Analyst + Community Analyst + Repo Explainer)
      ↓           all 3 via ThreadPoolExecutor(max_workers=3)
  write_report
      ↓
  gen_charts

State key: RepoState (TypedDict in graph/workflow.py)
Every node receives the full state and returns only the keys it changes.

## File Responsibilities — One File, One Job

app.py
  - Streamlit UI only
  - No business logic, no API calls, no data processing
  - Reads from session_state, calls analyse_repo(), displays results
  - Never import from agents/ directly

config.py
  - ALL settings live here and only here
  - Model name, temperature, API URLs, limits, suggested repos
  - Never hardcode these values anywhere else

graph/workflow.py
  - LangGraph StateGraph definition
  - Imports agents, wires them together, nothing else
  - analyse_repo(query) is the single public entry point

agents/repo_fetcher.py      - Agent 1: fetch all GitHub data, compute health score
agents/activity_analyst.py  - Agent 2: commit trends, release cadence, bus factor
agents/community_analyst.py - Agent 3: issue sentiment, maintainer responsiveness
agents/repo_explainer.py    - Agent 5: plain-English explanation of the repo
agents/report_writer.py     - Agent 4: synthesise final verdict and report
agents/chart_generator.py   - Agent 6: generate all Plotly charts

tools/github_tools.py
  - ALL GitHub API calls go here via _get() helper
  - LLM factory: get_llm() — never import ChatGroq in agents directly
  - health_score() — transparent arithmetic formula
  - parse_repo() — handles all input formats
  - fmt_number(), clean_output() — shared utilities

ui/styles.py
  - CSS injection via st.html() ONLY
  - Never use components.html() — it creates an iframe
  - Never use st.markdown() for CSS — it gets sanitised

ui/components.py
  - Reusable UI components: hero(), repo_header(), stats_row()
  - All HTML rendered via st.html() NOT st.markdown()
  - Never put business logic here

## Critical Rules

### CSS and HTML injection
ALWAYS use st.html() for any HTML or CSS.
NEVER use st.markdown(..., unsafe_allow_html=True) for HTML blocks.
NEVER use streamlit.components.v1.html() — it creates an iframe.

### LLM instantiation
ALWAYS: from tools.github_tools import get_llm; llm = get_llm()
NEVER: from langchain_groq import ChatGroq; llm = ChatGroq(...)

### GitHub API calls
ALWAYS go through tools/github_tools.py _get() helper
NEVER call requests.get("https://api.github.com/...") in agents

### Settings
ALWAYS import from config.py
NEVER hardcode model names, API URLs, limits, or repo names

### HTML inside Python strings
NEVER put # Python comments inside HTML f-strings
They are not stripped — they render as literal text in the browser

### health_score()
Formula is pure arithmetic — no LLM involved
Measures only verifiable signals from GitHub API
Do not add LLM-based scoring — it would make the formula unauditable

## Adding a New Agent

1. Create agents/your_agent.py with run_your_agent(repo_data) -> dict
2. Add your field to RepoState TypedDict in graph/workflow.py
3. Import and add to node_run_parallel() in workflow.py
4. Add to initial state dict in analyse_repo()
5. Display result in app.py

## Common Mistakes to Avoid

- Putting st.markdown HTML inside with col: blocks — use st.html()
- Importing analyse_repo before st.set_page_config() in app.py
- Making GitHub API calls without checking the response is not None
- Assuming commit_activity API returns instantly — it can return 202 (computing)
- Using st.markdown("---") thinking it's a divider everywhere — it is, but
  st.html("<hr>") can cause layout issues — stick to st.markdown("---")
